I'm so impressed by this drawing of me by Kaye Hodges @kayehodgesportraits. 
Somebody said it looks more like me than I do. I agree! A glimpse of someone at one moment in time may not represent a full picture of what they look like, but this gently hyper-realistic portrait describes me clearly at every point in the picture. And it's flattering because of the delicacy of the pencil work, rather than by omissions or fabrication. What I find particularly remarkable is that the shading on the skin shows precisely the distribution of tension and relaxation in my muscles that I recognise as being not only what I look like but what it feels like to be me. A little tiredness in the eyes, a little self-consciousness in the mouth, and a quiet alertness overall.

This piece was exhibited in London last year at the Society of Graphic Fine Art @drawingsocietyuk

Thank you Dark Odyssey for the incredible hard work and vision you put into creating this spectacular character.

~

I love the cerebral nature of this image. The text-like markings near the halo suggest the magic of this sorceress relates to words, logic and data - a type of magic that literally exists in our lives.

Dark Odyssey said he was going for an oracle vibe. It occurred to me as I happen to be writing from Iceland at the present moment, that the Icelandic word for computer is tölva, a feminine noun put together from tala (number) and völva (prophetess).

I actually think of computer programming as a real and true example of a magic spell! I'll try to explain. In computing there's a causal relationship between symbolic input and the physical behaviour of an inanimate system. Isn't that literally what witches and wizards try to do? They must express the symbols precisely correctly in order to influence the inanimate world in the way they intend. Yes, you might say, but it's not because of the meaning of the symbols that the computer behaves that way; it's been set up that way by humans so they can program it. True...but as far as I'm concerned, that IS a magic spell! We and all of the things that we make are as much a part of nature as anything else. As part of nature's hilarious tendency towards consciousness, we humans have made objects we can talk to and which talk back. I find this very funny and very awe-inspiring.

p.s. does anyone else think the sectioning on her chest makes a shape like an Aztec symbol?

At my last session modelling for @idehill.lifedrawing the theme was The Three Graces, and I was asked to dress in classical Grecian style.
In Greek mythology the Graces are known as the Charites, and in Roman, the Gratiae. They come as a trio and usually considered daughters of Zeus - Aglaea ("Shining"), Euphrosyne ("Joy"), and Thalia ("Blooming"). Their presence is believed to bring harmony, joy, and artistic inspiration to gods and mortals.
So...I did my best to bring the Graces to Ide Hill, and the artists placed my poses together in groups of three.
As usual I improvised my costume. My 'toga' is a skirt with the inner lining pulled up and pinned over one shoulder with a safety pin. I did my makeup without outlining my eyes, to give a clean, sculptural look - because sculptures and goddesses in Renaissance paintings don't have much in the way of eyelashes. At the last moment I remembered the strips of curly dark hair that I'd had sitting in a box for years, knowing they'd come in handy at some point. In hindsight I think this was the (hair)pièce de résistance. I loved seeing how each artist rendered the curly whirly shapes with their different signature squiggles.

By the way, the theme I've been given for my next session is Toulouse-Lautrec's dancers.

This is the sort of semi-abstract, semi-emotive freestyle posing that I love to do when given a simple space to pose in. The photographer's role is usually then to give me micro-directions such as "move your left elbow towards me" and my job is to figure out my left from right while my brain's body map is all tangled up (I only get it wrong 50% of the time!). James did a fabulous job micro-adjusting my poses in this session. Take it from me: it's such a worthwhile thing to do when working with a model, because even if they seem to pose with inspiration and confidence, those little details that the photographer can see often make the difference between an almost-usable photo and an iconic image.

Using a shampoo bar to wash my hair is taking some getting used to, but my hair has felt VERY clean and ever so light every time I've washed it with my Yao Secret ricewater shampoo bar. As someone having an on-off relationship with my emerging silver strands I was curious to try anything organic that might, possibly, maybe, help me hold onto my brunette babeness for a teensy bit longer.

[content warning: misery]
In a few days time, I will take the last anti-depressant pill I’ll ever take. That’s the plan. After 18 years, I have little knowledge of what I’m like as an adult without that chemical intervention, but what I do know is quite terrifying. I’ve dipped my toe in that cold water a handful of times, each time recoiling after several months because of suffering that wasn't merely debilitating but outright cognitively intolerable. The difference is that this time I’m going into it very intentionally, gradually, with no expectation that it will be OK, as opposed to whimsically abandoning my medicine in the wake of a positive circumstantial twist (such as falling in love - bleurgh!). This time I’ve written notes to my future self, which will be lifelines when I’ve lost my grip on reality. One of my notes simply says: WRITE. So I’m starting now, before I go over the edge. I predict from experience that in some months’ time I’ll be looking back on these weeks where I experienced sorrow, anger, frustration and being a twat to people, and miss the richness of that humanity. Soon enough my emotions will be simplified into a binary distinction: fear and hope, with hope shrinking to a tiny, bright speck on the horizon and fear being a heavy black cloud over everything else, billowing over all my inside surfaces, following me into every chamber of my mind to poison my memories and beliefs.
Why would I do this dark thing during the coming of winter? I don’t know…there’s a harmony to it. My usually-bleak January will be one of the bleakest ever, but who knows, I might discover a new self with the coming of spring and its healing powers.
I’m doing this publicly because I hope some people will find it useful or fascinating to observe my misery, and also because I want to be held accountable for my intention to WRITE. I have been known to scribble occasional humorous poems about dr*gs, consciousness and suffering... 
Let’s do this thing!

My body cannot move into the fullness of the present until my mind has unpuzzled the tangled disturbances of my recent past. But there is an invisible, infinity thin plane of reality in which I can dwell in nothing but my breath.

I asked my little friend ChatGPT this question: “After a betrayal, how do I tell the difference between acknowledging my emotions in order to process them healthily, vs clinging unhelpfully to my intrusive thoughts?”

It came up with a list of tips, two of which I found particularly helpful, especially considered in combination:

“1. **Mindfulness:** Practice mindfulness to become aware of your thoughts and emotions without judgment. Mindfulness can help you observe your feelings without necessarily attaching yourself to them.

2. **Set Boundaries:** Allow yourself a designated time to think about the betrayal and your emotions. After that time, try to redirect your focus to other aspects of your life.”

As somebody who’s intensely dominated by thought, it’s never helped me to be told to “stop overthinking” something. But by observing my thoughts from a detached level and creating designated boundaries in time, I can protect my mind in a way that honours its thoughtful nature rather than dismissing it.

I’m uncomfortable sharing it but that’s why I’m doing it. Most of my modelling photos don’t deviate far from a neutral facial expression, and when they do it’s not usually towards sorrow. Emotions like sorrow are often represented metaphorically in a photo via the colours and lighting. But I come fully equipped with a range of human emotions, so why not use them in my images? As a professional model I’ve become adept at masking negative emotions. But having a photographer for a life partner comes with a certain mix of curses and blessings. As well as regularly eliciting the entire range of my possible emotional states to the fullest, my photographer-partner is also in the best position to capture those moments as they happen.
It was one month ago that I embarked on a trip that would turn out to be one of the most emotionally painful times in my life. We took these photos a few days after we returned. The feelings were (and still are) very raw. The November cold was unexpectedly comforting, because of its cleansing purity and its familiarity. After the bewildering torment of the nightmare where I was stripped of my powers in a strange place, stepping back onto home turf was such a relief that I didn’t mind the damp and chilly weather at all. I began the slow process of putting myself back together. The painful facts still flood my mind whenever I wake up and when I go to sleep, but the daytimes are just starting to blush faintly with different colours - muted tones of feelings I remember from before, which aren’t grief or anger. One day soon, I think I’ll wake up feeling something different,and it will be the beginning of the next chapter of my life.

In 2023 I was dealt a mini series of trials and tribulations to test me. Shortly after coming off my antidepressants after 18 years, I experienced the extraordinary pain of betrayal in an exceptionally brutal way - and then in the wake of this complex situation my body started some physically excruciating drama of its own and I lost a fallopian tube to an ectopic pregnancy (arrived home from hospital in time to celebrate my birthday yesterday).

It's too poetic, almost comedic, for me to cast myself as unlucky - instead I'm rather impressed, picturing the gods laughing and congratulating themselves as they watch me scurrying around, exhausted, trying to pick up the pieces of my life and figure out how best to fit them back together.

I'm glad they carefully arranged things so as to begin with the transformation that peeled my soul raw, heightening my sensitivity to fear, shame and horror, and then delivered my losses in swift subsequent succession. Timing it all to coincide with the bleakness of winter was a stroke of genius too, and I can take some of the credit for that, because I chose for the early phases of my antidepressants withdrawal to take place during my least favourite time of the year (now), along with any negative consequences this might have on my life - and fate did not disappoint. I damaged my ability to love and be loved.

I'm as desperate as an atheist can possibly be, to believe that my betrayal was meant for me, rather than a mere consequence of someone else's disappointing shortcomings. It's not even enough for me to see it as a punishment for my half-hearted, begrudgingly-performed fake sacrifices. I tell myself that I did it. "I did it. I did it. And I enjoyed it, too!"

I'm on a rescue mission to rediscover the love that went missing when the betrayer punched that ugly hole through my heart, and the answers are to be found in the daunting caverns where he hid his hatred for me...a place where I will finally see my reflection clearly.

Carl Jung
